455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1482":"1482","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"en":{"1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1435–1489":"1435–1489","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1482":"1482","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Williamson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northern) and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name   William   + patronymic <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>William</i>’. This surname is also found in Northern Ireland (Ulster), especially in Antrim.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Wilhelmsen  , Swedish <b>Wilhelmsson</b>, or Dutch and North German   Willemsen  , all cognates of 1.","History: This surname was brought to North America from northern England and northern Ireland independently by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. Timothy Williamson is recorded in Plymouth Colony in 1643."],"variants":[{"name":"Willamson","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Williamson  ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Henry Williamson was born in 1430, in Christchurch, Hampshire, England, his father, William Robert Williamson II, was 27 and his mother, Lady Mary Robertson, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Lady Anne Haddle. He died in 1488, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1435–1489":"1435–1489","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1482":"1482","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1435–1489":"1435–1489","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1482":"1482","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1435–1489":"1435–1489","1455–1503":"1455–1503","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Décédée","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1482":"1482","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Angleterre","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir John Henry Williamson est né en 1430, à Christchurch, Hampshire, Angleterre, son père, William Robert Williamson II, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Lady Mary Robertson, avait 20 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lady Anne Haddle. Il est décédé en 1488, à Londres, Middlesex, Angle